const faqs = [{"question": "What should I eat on semaglutide to maximize weight loss?", "answer": "Focus on lean proteins (chicken, fish, eggs, Greek yogurt), non-starchy vegetables, complex carbohydrates in moderate portions (quinoa, sweet potatoes, legumes), and healthy fats (avocado, olive oil, nuts). Protein matters most here. Aim for 25–30% of your calories from protein to protect lean muscle mass while you're losing weight. Small, frequent meals (4–5 per day) tend to sit better than 2–3 large ones."}, {"question": "Can I follow a keto diet while on semaglutide?", "answer": "Strict keto isn't a good fit with semaglutide for most people. Severely cutting carbs while the medication already suppresses your appetite creates a real risk of inadequate calorie intake, nutrient gaps, and worse GI side effects. A moderate-carb approach (30–40% of calories) built around whole grains and legumes tends to work better and feels more sustainable."}, {"question": "How much weight can I lose with semaglutide and proper diet?", "answer": "In the STEP 1 trial, participants on semaglutide 2.4 mg lost an average of 14.9% of body weight over 68 weeks. That's roughly 33 lbs for a 220 lb person. Patients who added structured diet and exercise programs (as in STEP 3) lost even more, averaging 16% body weight reduction. Your results will depend on starting weight, how closely you follow dietary changes, physical activity, and individual metabolic factors."}, {"question": "Why do I feel nauseous after eating on semaglutide?", "answer": "Nausea is the most common side effect, hitting 40–44% of participants in clinical trials. It happens because GLP-1 slows gastric emptying, so food sits in your stomach longer than you're used to. Eating smaller portions, skipping greasy and fried foods, eating slowly, and stopping at the first hint of fullness all help. Most patients notice the nausea fading after 4–8 weeks as their body adjusts."}, {"question": "Do I need to follow a special diet on semaglutide, or will the medication work on its own?", "answer": "Semaglutide alone produces real weight loss. But structured dietary changes make a noticeable difference. The STEP 3 trial paired semaglutide with intensive behavioral therapy (including diet counseling) and saw greater results than medication alone. Beyond the scale, a nutrient-dense diet protects lean muscle mass, supports your overall health, and builds eating habits that hold up if you eventually stop the medication."}, {"question": "What happens to my diet when I stop semaglutide?", "answer": "The STEP 4 trial showed that patients who stopped semaglutide regained about two-thirds of their lost weight within a year. That's why building solid eating habits during treatment matters so much. Patients who lock in a structured eating pattern while on the medication have a better shot at keeping weight off long-term. A physician-supervised tapering plan helps too."}, {"question": "How much protein should I eat on semaglutide?", "answer": "Aim for 1.0–1.2 grams of protein per kilogram of ideal body weight daily. That usually works out to 25–30% of total calories. High protein intake is critical for protecting lean muscle mass during rapid weight loss. Spread your protein across all meals and snacks instead of loading it into a single sitting. Good sources: chicken, fish, eggs, Greek yogurt, cottage cheese, and legumes."}, {"question": "Is semaglutide safe for long-term use?", "answer": "The SELECT trial tracked over 17,600 participants for an average of 33 months. Semaglutide reduced major cardiovascular events by 20%. The FDA has approved it for chronic weight management, meaning it's designed for ongoing use. Common side effects (nausea, diarrhea, constipation) tend to fade over time. Rare but serious risks include pancreatitis and gallbladder disease. Your physician should supervise long-term use with regular monitoring."}, {"question": "Could medical weight loss with GLP-1 therapy be right for me?", "answer": "GLP-1 therapy fits best if you have a BMI of 30 or above (or 27+ with a weight-related health condition), you've tried diet and exercise without reaching your goals, and you want physician-supervised support. A free assessment with a qualified provider helps determine whether you're a candidate based on your health history, current medications, and goals."}, {"question": "How does semaglutide compare to other weight loss medications?", "answer": "Semaglutide (Wegovy) produces roughly 15% body weight loss, well ahead of older medications like phentermine (5–7%) or orlistat (3–5%). The newer tirzepatide (Mounjaro/Zepbound), a dual GIP/GLP-1 agonist, has shown even larger reductions (up to 22.5% in the SURMOUNT-1 trial). Your physician will help you decide which option fits your profile."}];

